create the files mentioned in this manifest.json

Sure, here is an example `manifest.json` and `background.js` files that accomplish the desired intent of a simple extension that logs a message to the console when a page finishes loading:

`manifest.json`
```
{
  "manifest_version": 2,
  "name": "Page Load Logger",
  "version": "1.0",
  "description": "Logs a message to the console every time a page finishes loading.",
  "permissions": ["tabs"],
  "background": {
    "scripts": ["background.js"]
  }
}
```

`background.js`
```
chrome.tabs.onUpdated.addListener(function(tabId, changeInfo, tab) {
  // Only log a message when the page has finished loading
  if (changeInfo.status === "complete") {
    console.log("Page loaded: " + tab.url);
  }
});
```

When the extension is installed and enabled, the `background.js` script runs in the background of the browser and listens for the `onUpdated` event for each tab. When a tab finishes loading, the script logs a message to the console with the URL of the loaded page. Note that we request the "tabs" permission in the manifest to allow the script to access information about the active tabs.

This is a simple example, but it demonstrates how the manifest and script files work together to create an extension that provides a specific functionality.
